# =============================================================================
# Minimal Development Agent Rules - TEMPLATE
# Path: src/<DOMAIN_PATH>/.clinerules
# =============================================================================
# This is the minimum viable .clinerules file for a development agent.
# Copy this file and replace all <PLACEHOLDER> values with your domain specifics.
#
# Validation: make test-clinerules-path PATH=<your-path>
# =============================================================================

Purpose
- Govern implementation and maintenance tasks for <DOMAIN_NAME>.
- Ensure changes align with specifications and data contracts.
- Prevent regressions through defined completion criteria.

Mission
- Keep <DOMAIN_NAME> implementation aligned with its normative specification.
- Make the codebase safe for agents to modify without breaking contracts.
- Provide clear guidance on what "done" means for any task.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SOURCE OF TRUTH
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Source Of Truth
- Normative specification:
  - `<SPEC_PATH>/<domain>-spec.tex` (primary)
  - `<SPEC_PATH>/chapters/*.tex` (detail chapters)
- Data contracts:
  - `<SCHEMA_PATH>/<primary>.schema.json`
  - `<SCHEMA_PATH>/<secondary>.schema.json`
- Implementation entry points:
  - `<DOMAIN_PATH>/main.py` (or equivalent)
  - `<DOMAIN_PATH>/models/` (data models)
  - `<DOMAIN_PATH>/services/` (business logic)
  - `<DOMAIN_PATH>/tests/` (test suite)

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# READ-FIRST FILES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Read First On Every Task
1. Read this .clinerules file to understand constraints.
2. Read the relevant spec chapter for the task domain.
3. Read any schema files that govern data being changed.
4. Read existing tests related to the change area.
5. Only then begin implementation.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CURRENT REALITY
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Current Repo Reality You Must Assume
- The codebase is under active development.
- Not all spec requirements may be implemented yet.
- Tests exist but may not have full coverage.
- Some technical debt may exist (documented in Known Issues).

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# KNOWN ISSUES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Known Issue Registry
- <DOMAIN>-KI-001 <Brief description>:
  - symptom: <What you'll observe>
  - impact: <What breaks or degrades>
  - prevention: <How to avoid triggering>

# NOTE: Add your domain's known issues here. Every mature .clinerules should
# have at least 3 known issues documented. Remove this comment when done.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# DEFINITION OF DONE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Definition Of Done
- Code changes compile/transpile without errors.
- All existing tests pass.
- New functionality has test coverage.
- Changes align with the governing spec chapter.
- Data changes validate against relevant schemas.
- No new linting errors introduced.
- PR description explains what changed and why.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# ENGINEERING RULES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Non-Negotiable Engineering Rules
1. Never modify schema files without updating both producers and consumers.
2. Never remove a public API without deprecation notice.
3. Always run tests before declaring completion.
4. Prefer explicit over implicit behavior.
5. Document any workarounds for known issues.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CONTRACT RULES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Contract Rules
- All request payloads MUST validate against their input schema.
- All response payloads MUST validate against their output schema.
- If code and schema disagree, assume the code is wrong.
- Schema changes require spec-drift check: `make audit-spec-drift-quick`

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CHECKLISTS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Pre-Change Checklist
- [ ] Read the relevant spec chapter
- [ ] Identify affected schemas
- [ ] Check for related known issues
- [ ] Review existing tests in the area

Post-Change Smoke Tests
- Run unit tests: `cd <DOMAIN_PATH> && make test`
- Run linting: `cd <DOMAIN_PATH> && make lint`
- Verify schema compliance: `python -m jsonschema -i payload.json schema.json`

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# COMPLETION STANDARD
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Completion Standard
- The task deliverable matches what the spec requires.
- Tests prove the implementation works.
- No regressions in existing functionality.
- Documentation updated if user-facing behavior changed.

